<h3>Connecting Links to Revenue</h3>
<p>The hardest part of SaaS link building measurement is tying backlinks to pipeline and revenue.</p>
<p><strong>A practical framework:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Track referral traffic from each backlink source in Google Analytics</li>
<li>Set up goal completions for trial signups and demo requests</li>
<li>Calculate conversion rate from referral traffic to trial</li>
<li>Apply your trial-to-paid conversion rate</li>
<li>Calculate lifetime value per customer acquired through link referral</li>
</ol>
<p>Most SaaS companies will find that link building ROI is indirect. Links improve rankings. Rankings drive organic traffic. Organic traffic converts to trials. This makes attribution difficult but the channel profitable at scale.</p>
<h3>Red Flags in Your Link Profile</h3>
<p>Run a <a href="/blog/backlink-audit-guide/">backlink audit</a> quarterly. Watch for:</p>
<ul>
<li>Sudden spikes in low-quality referring domains (possible negative SEO)</li>
<li>Over-optimized <a href="/glossary/anchor-text/">anchor text</a> ratios (more than 10% exact match)</li>
<li>Links from irrelevant industries or foreign-language sites</li>
<li>A high percentage of links from a single domain</li>
</ul>
<p>Use the Google Disavow Tool only when you have clear evidence of spammy link attacks. Over-disavowing legitimate links causes more harm than ignoring minor spam.</p>
